english:
  title: Record of the Yinbin Hall in Yingri County
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: On the shores of the Eastern Sea stands a county called Yingri, also known as Lintin—the eastern frontier of Silla in ancient days. In Silla's infancy, when culture had not yet bloomed and institutions remained unformed, there came a middle age when virtuous rulers succeeded one another. Then did the kingdom open to the Middle Kingdom, searching through its texts and records. Morning sun and evening moon are inscribed in the national chronicles, and the welcoming and farewell of the sun recorded in the ancient sage-kings' annals. Thus the ancients deemed that imperial governance, in revering Heaven and establishing seasons for mankind, need amount to no more than this. Though lacking in ancestral precedent, such customs could still be justified by principle. Official positions were established, including the Grand Historian, and towers were raised to observe the stars. In time, the systems of calendars, celestial measurements, and instruments of gnomon were gradually perfected. In that era, this county lay in the direction of the Valley of the Rising Sun, and thus it received its name. When Koryo's Great Founder reformed the succession of ages, he abandoned the name Lintin and restored the present name—was this not for good reason?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yingri (迎日) literally means 'welcoming the sun,' referring to the easternmost location where the sun first rises
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'the Valley of the Rising Sun' (暘谷) is from Chinese cosmological tradition, believed to be where the sun originates each day
  - key: ''
    value: Lintin (臨汀) means 'facing the waters,' reflecting the county's coastal geography
  - key: ''
    value: The Hall is named 'Yinbin' (寅賓), where 寅 refers to the Tiger hour (3-5 AM) and 賓 means 'to receive as guest,' thus 'receiving the dawn'—a poetic reference to greeting the sunrise
